{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566031"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:36:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:36:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18700"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.67,0.21,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97808"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8862"},{"type":"tags","id":"8951"},{"type":"tags","id":"9013"},{"type":"tags","id":"9640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97808"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive fatigue, difficulty with handwriting, and personality changes noted by his partner. He works in a lead smelter and has been in this role for two years. His medical history includes mild asthma, for which he uses a salbutamol inhaler when required. He does not take any other regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with mild hepatomegaly and right upper quadrant tenderness. Neurological examination reveals dysarthria, a postural tremor in both hands, and mild cogwheel rigidity. Slit lamp examination shows brown rings at the periphery of both corneas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 145 g/L (130-170)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlanine transferase: 156 U/L (5-40)\u003Cbr /\u003EAspartate transferase: 142 U/L (5-40)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlkaline phosphatase: 145 U/L (30-110)\u003Cbr /\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase: 168 U/L (5-50)\u003Cbr /\u003EBilirubin: 32 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin: 32 g/L (35-50)\u003Cbr /\u003ECeruloplasmin: 150 mg/L (200-600)\u003Cbr /\u003EFerritin: 320 \u00b5g/L (30-300)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary biliary cholangitis","Wilson disease","Lead toxicity","Haemochromatosis","Chronic viral hepatitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of Wilson disease: hepatic dysfunction, neurological symptoms (dysarthria, tremor, cogwheel rigidity), and Kayser-Fleischer rings. The low ceruloplasmin is also consistent with Wilsons disease. The Leipzig scoring system is used to diagnose Wilson disease, incorporating: Kayser-Fleischer rings (2 points), neurological symptoms (2 points), low ceruloplasmin (1 point), Coombs-negative haemolytic anaemia (1 point), elevated urinary copper (2 points), elevated liver copper content (1 point), and rhodanine-positive hepatocytes (1 point). A score of 4 or more confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal recessive disorder of copper metabolism that leads to copper accumulation in various tissues, particularly the liver and brain. The markedly low ceruloplasmin level (150 mg/L) is particularly significant as this is the main copper-binding protein in blood. The presence of Kayser-Fleischer rings (brown rings in the cornea) is pathognomonic when combined with neurological symptoms. The liver function tests show a hepatocellular pattern of injury with reduced synthetic function (low albumin). The mildly elevated ferritin is consistent with inflammatory liver disease and does not suggest iron overload.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELead toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E can cause neurological symptoms including peripheral neuropathy, encephalopathy, and tremor. However, it would not cause Kayser-Fleischer rings or low ceruloplasmin levels. Lead toxicity typically presents with anaemia, basophilic stippling of red blood cells, and a lead line on the gums, none of which are present in this case. The patient\u0027s haemoglobin is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic viral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fatigue and liver dysfunction but would not explain the neurological symptoms, Kayser-Fleischer rings, or copper metabolism abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary biliary cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects middle-aged women and presents with fatigue, pruritus, and elevated alkaline phosphatase. It would not cause the copper metabolism abnormalities or neurological symptoms seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemochromatosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a disorder of iron metabolism, not copper metabolism. While it can cause liver dysfunction, it would not explain the neurological symptoms or the copper-related findings. Additionally, in haemochromatosis, ferritin levels are typically much higher than seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Wilson disease presents with the triad of liver dysfunction, neurological symptoms, and Kayser-Fleischer rings.","Low serum ceruloplasmin (\u003C200 mg/L) is a key diagnostic feature of Wilson disease.","The Leipzig scoring system combines clinical, biochemical and genetic findings to diagnose Wilson disease.","Kayser-Fleischer rings are pathognomonic for Wilson disease when combined with neurological symptoms."],"references":["Roberts EA, Schilsky ML. Diagnosis and treatment of Wilson disease: an update. Hepatology. 2008;47(6):2089-2111 Available at: https://aasldpubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com","UpToDate. Wilson disease: Clinical manifestations, diagnosis, and natural history. Waltham, MA: UpToDate Available at: https://www.uptodate.com","Ferenci P. Pathophysiology and clinical features of Wilson disease. Metab Brain Dis. 2004;19(3-4):229-239 Available at: https://link.springer.com"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80363"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T14:46:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T16:10:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11432"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97808"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud